# Edit this file to define your project goal before running the baton loop.
#
# Full requirements, architecture decisions, and implementation detail are in:
#   prd.yaml — Multi-Tenant RAG Chat Platform (v1.0.0 PoC)
#
# This file is the concise entry point. Refer to prd.yaml for:
#   - Key design decisions (DEC-001 through DEC-009)
#   - Full database schema and API endpoint contracts
#   - RAG retrieval & relevance strategy
#   - CDK stack breakdown (SharedStack, TenantStack, UIStack)
#   - File handling, session limits, and cleanup policy
#   - Non-functional requirements and security guardrails
#
project_goal: >
  Build a multi-tenant RAG chat platform where each tenant gets an isolated
  AI assistant backed by their own Bedrock Knowledge Base and Bedrock Agent.
  A single Nuxt 4 codebase is deployed per tenant (same Docker image, different
  TENANT_ID env var) on ECS Fargate. All backend logic lives in Nuxt server routes
  (no separate API service). Aurora Serverless v2 stores sessions, messages, and
  file metadata. Uploaded files are stored in S3 and passed to Bedrock by S3
  reference. Responses stream via SSE. Infrastructure is fully automated with
  AWS CDK in TypeScript. Auth is Google OAuth (nuxt-google-auth) for PoC.

success_criteria:
  - A user can open the chat UI, ask a question, and receive a streamed response
    grounded in the tenant's knowledge base documents with source citations
  - A second tenant deployment (different TENANT_ID) returns answers only from
    its own KB — no cross-tenant content appears in any response
  - A user can upload a file (PDF, DOCX, TXT) in a chat session and the assistant
    references its content in subsequent turns within the same session
  - Session history persists across browser refreshes — messages reload correctly
    from Aurora via GET /api/sessions/:id/messages
  - CDK deploy (cdk deploy --all) provisions SharedStack, TenantStack, and UIStack
    from scratch without manual console steps
  - Bedrock Agent returns a KB limitation message (not a hallucinated answer)
    when a question has no relevant content in the tenant knowledge base
  - Retrieval pipeline uses semantic chunking, top_k=12 candidates, Bedrock
    reranking to top 5, and strict grounding (guardrail threshold 0.75)
  - POST /api/files enforces max 5 files, 10MB per file, 20 files per session,
    and validates MIME type server-side before writing to S3
  - All infrastructure secrets (Aurora credentials, OAuth secrets) are stored in
    Secrets Manager — nothing hardcoded in code or CDK assets

context_notes:
  - Stack is full TypeScript — Nuxt 4 (UI + server routes via h3/Nitro) + CDK
  - One Bedrock Agent per tenant, one Bedrock KB per tenant — hard resource isolation,
    not metadata-filter isolation
  - Aurora Serverless v2 shared cluster with per-tenant vector schema
    (vectors_{tenantId}) and shared app schema (sessions, messages, session_files)
  - Bedrock KB uses Aurora pgvector as vector store via RDS Data API (semantic only,
    no hybrid retrieval for PoC)
  - Files are uploaded via POST /api/files → stored in S3 with key pattern
    tenant-files-{env}/{tenantId}/{userId}/{sessionId}/{fileId}/{filename},
    metadata in app.session_files; chat passes S3 source reference to Bedrock
    (not byte content) — avoids server-side byte download on every turn
  - Streaming uses fetch() POST + ReadableStream reader — NOT EventSource
    (EventSource is GET-only and cannot carry a request body)
  - tenantId is baked into the ECS task at deploy time via NUXT_PUBLIC_TENANT_ID
    env var — it cannot be overridden by a browser caller
  - Per-tenant ECS service is PoC architecture only; production will consolidate
    to a single shared service with subdomain-based tenant routing
  - Authenticated direct Aurora access is permitted in dev/PoC environments to
    reduce development friction (see DEC-009 guardrails) — not for production
  - Google OAuth via nuxt-google-auth is the recommended PoC auth path (~2hr setup);
    fallback is browser UUID in localStorage if auth is deferred

constraints:
  - No autonomous background runtime
  - No heavy phase orchestration engine
  - No unnecessary microservices or clever abstractions
  - No separate API service — all backend logic in Nuxt server routes only
  - No Lambda functions for application logic (CDK schema-setup Lambda is the only exception)
  - No DynamoDB — Aurora handles sessions, file metadata, and vectors
  - No shared Bedrock Agent or KB across tenants — one agent and one KB per tenant, always
  - No production customer data in dev/PoC environments
  - No hardcoded secrets in source code or CDK assets

